I was listening to Pastor Armstrong&rsquo;s lesson in 1 Corinthians 10 at about the 27 minute mark when the buzzer on my dryer went off. I hit pause just on the back side of him saying, &ldquo;&hellip;confidence is not a sign of spiritual maturity. It is a sign of spiritual immaturity that you think you&hellip;can be oblivious to [the] temptation&hellip;that you assume you&rsquo;ll never fall. The mature Christian is the one who recognizes the danger and the strength of the flesh.&rdquo;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;

I was considering this and making application &ndash; not hard to do considering my on-going and re-energized battle with my flesh &ndash; as I headed to the laundry room. I was thinking that in my reality if I am to live as a spiritually mature Christian, I probably should not buy M&amp;Ms to put in the freezer, telling myself that they&rsquo;re for cookies, while opening the top for easy access as I come and go throughout the day. No, that probably is not a sign of maturity. I was barely to the laundry room with these thoughts when I heard my husband&rsquo;s text tone on my phone and went to see the message.

