Hello, Melissa. God calling!! 

Notice how spiritually mature I was? &lsquo;No&hellip;don&rsquo;t bring them home for me,&rsquo; wink wink. I stood there in abject indecision before sending my reply, knowing what I should say (take the exit ramp!!), and absolutely powerless to say it. I stood there staring at those glazed rings of hell knowing that if they come into my home I will eat them. The decision to not decide was my decision, because I know that unless the Lord intervenes or comes again, when my husband arrives home an hour from now, he will be bearing the famed green, red, and white box with those little hellish puffs of lovelies inside. Then I will face another decision, because one indulgence of the flesh leads to another. And it&rsquo;s just this simple. Everything Paul was teaching the Corinthians in chapters 8-10 is right here on a plate. Or in a box, as the case may be.

If you haven&rsquo;t listened to this audio teaching&nbsp;(Lesson 10A) on the website, I would suggest that you head on over there right now if you have any kind of battle with your flesh. Or just hit your knees with the open Book, turn straight there, and just this one time you can skip the context, because I know you&rsquo;re looking at that picture above and&nbsp;thinking to yourself, &ldquo;Eating a donut isn&rsquo;t a sin.&rdquo; To which I would agree -&nbsp;in theory.

In practice, it&rsquo;s another thing altogether, and that is the essence of Paul&rsquo;s point in these chapters. He&rsquo;s telling us that, &ldquo;He who would not fall down ought not walk in slippery places&rdquo; even if (especially if) he thinks he&rsquo;s sure-footed. I forget who said that, but it is the gist of this passage. If you&rsquo;re like my husband, when you look at those fried delights what you see is flour and sugar and oil, none of which you need in your very healthy body. When I look at them, I taste them, I feel them, I smell them, and it is pure hedonistic joy to me just imagining putting one in my mouth. I cannot possibly resist the temptation if I invite them into my kitchen! You see the problem.

You have one of these things too: something that maybe has no appeal to me, but gives you a rush of pure bliss just in the imagining. We all have them. And when&nbsp;accommodated without restraint, they all lead us to sin and death and hell (not speaking of salvation, but of misery in our spiritual life and the loss of our rewards). Freedom indulged can lead to sinful indulgence. It&rsquo;s the walk down the primrose path. It&rsquo;s the slippery slope. It is a nearly irreversible course.&nbsp;

So now, the decisions remain before me. Will I deny my liberty to eat that donut, or exercise it? Will I act with maturity or immaturity? Will I trade an eternal reward for that bite? Will it be worth it when I know what I forfeited? Will I worship God or self? These are my exit ramps. They are many, and varied, and flush with blessings, but will they be enough to make me flee&hellip;?

Dear Lord, give me the self-discipline to beat my body and make it my slave!&nbsp;

