Have you ever met someone who had an immediate and positive impact on your outlook for life? In my life such meetings have been rare but they have happened. I was recently blessed when I met a friend of a friend while out at lunch. Our introduction began in a normal fashion:

	&ldquo;Kevin, meet my friend, Brady.&rdquo;

	&ldquo;Kevin? Hi! Nice to meet you.&rdquo;

	&ldquo;Nice to meet you, too!&rdquo;

	We exchanged the normal pleasantries, asking each other how long we had known Chad, our mutual friend: are you married, have any kids, etc. Then the conversation turned to work.

	&ldquo;So, Kevin, what do you do?&rdquo;

	&ldquo;I&rsquo;m in the import business.&rdquo;

	Chad turned to him with a shocked look on his face. &ldquo;Did you lose your job at the bank? You&rsquo;ve been there for years! What happened?&rdquo;

	Kevin smiled at him. &ldquo;Yes, I still work at the bank but Brady didn&rsquo;t ask what my job was. He asked what I do.&rdquo;

	He turned to me to explain, &ldquo;Although I work at a bank as a job to provide for my family, what I have been charged to do by my Creator is be an importer.&rdquo;

	Kevin must have notice the puzzled look on my face because he went on.

	&nbsp;&ldquo;For the past few hundred years Christianity has made finding salvation the goal of their evangelistic work: once a person is saved then their work is done." He wiped his hands together as if finishing a task. "The Bible, however, describes salvation as merely the introduction to much greater work: the import business. Believers are supposed to import G-d&rsquo;s holiness and righteousness into this world.&rdquo;

	&ldquo;In the heavenly realm of G-d&rsquo;s kingdom everything that is said and done is imbued with G-d&rsquo;s perfect holiness and righteousness. Because of the fallen state of our earthly realm, G-d has withdrawn Himself from it&hellip; to some degree. It says in James 2:5 that &lsquo;G-d has chosen the poor of this world to be rich in faith and heirs to the kingdom which He promised to those who love Him.&rsquo; James was talking about you and me! We are heirs to the kingdom.&rdquo;

	&ldquo;Although we live in the kingdom of this world (for now) we are citizens of G-d&rsquo;s kingdom. It&#39;s like we&#39;re traveling abroad on business and our job is to import holiness and righteousness from our true kingdom, G-d&rsquo;s kingdom, into this world. As Christ said in Matthew 5:16, &lsquo;Let your light shine before men in such a way that they may see your good works, and glorify your Father who is in heaven.&rsquo; Although Christ&rsquo;s kingdom has not yet been fully established on the earth (that won&rsquo;t fully happen until He returns) we are members of His kingdom now and, with the help and guidance of the Holy Spirit, we can live our lives in a way that reflects that truth."

	Kevin grinned and said, &ldquo;OK&hellip; technically speaking we have two jobs. We need to be importers and we need to teach others to be importers as well.&rdquo;

	We continued our conversation for a while and then parted ways. I left our meeting blessed and encouraged&hellip; and with a new understanding of who I am in G-d&rsquo;s kingdom.

